{
  "text": "The controversially high content of atropine (0.95%), a toxic alkaloid naturally present in Goji fruit, was tested in berries from India in 1989. However, published case reports do not describe people who have experienced atropine poisoning [CITATION_1] . Adams et al. [2006] carefully tested atropine levels by means of HPLC-PAD and TLC methods. They were not able to detect atropine. Using HPLC-MS, a small amount of atropine was found, with a maximum content of 19 ppb, well below a toxic level.",
